Okay. So uh growing up in Texas, I lived in Texas all my life. I was born in Titus County. And when I
was five we moved to a farm near White House, which is south east of Ty- Tyler, sorry. I like growing
up in the country. When my chores were done, I'd ride my horse, climb trees or hike down uh, the creek
to fish or swim. One time we tied a rope to a limb of the cypress tree we - and we would swing out wide,
over the swimming hole and drop into the water. I pretend to be Tarzan swinging on the vine. In the
spring, I fly kites and on summer nights we'd catch fireflies. We would call them lightning bugs. Once in
a while, we would have fights in the corncob or pine cones. In-in-in-in the winter, we'd build to fire in the
fireplace and pop popcorn and roast peanuts and pecans. I guess I was a live wire. When I was 19, I
went to work in Dallas at the- at a Firestone Tire store. I didn't like city life. For a long time, I would go
home every chance I got. Mama would always cook my favorite foods, fried okra, hoppin john, that rice
and the black eyed peas and pecan pie. We had a lot of good times, but going home was not the same
now after daddy died. Okay, but going home, it's not the same. Now. After daddy died, Mama sold the
farm and moved to Tyler. I rather be living on a farm right now instead of here in the city, but my wife
and kids don't understand when I gripe about the city life and talk about moving to the country. Uh-uh-
um my oldest child said, "Daddy, that's crazy. I'd just die if I had to live on a farm." I almost cried for the
first time when she said that. I know Texas is changing. But I try to make sure we don't lose in touch
with our roots. While we may live in the city, I want my kids to have the good feeling for the land, have a
sense of place and take pride in being Texans. If we lose our ties to the land, the price of progress is
too high. [PAUSE] Is that exactly my story that I was talking about-
